====Immigration====
Starting in the year 2010, for the first time since the [[California Gold Rush]], California-born residents make up the majority of the state's population.<ref>{{cite news |title=Native-born Californians regain majority status |author=Teresa Watanabe |author2=Hector Becerra |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/01/local/la-me-homegrown1-2010apr01 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=April 1, 2010 |accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref> In 2011, California saw a shift in its immigration pattern, with more coming from [[Asia]] and less from [[Latin America]].<ref name="SacBee17JAN2013" /> In total for 2011, there were 277,304 immigrants. 57% came from Asian countries vs. 22% from Latin American countries.<ref name="SacBee17JAN2013">{{cite news |title=Census shows Asians eclipse Latino arrivals to California |author=Stephen Magagnini |author2=Phillip Reese |url=http://www.sacbee.com/2013/01/17/5120459/asian-immigrants-to-california.html |newspaper=Sacramento Bee |date=January 17, 2013 |accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref>

The state's population of [[illegal immigrants]] has been shrinking in recent years, due to increased enforcement and a slumping economy.<ref>[http://www.pewhispanic.org/2012/12/06/unauthorized-immigrants-11-1-million-in-2011/ Pew Hispanic Center]</ref> The number of migrants arrested attempting to cross the Mexican border in the Southwest plunged from a high of 1.1 million in 2005 to just 367,000 in 2011.<ref name="BusinessWeek">[http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-05-03/californias-illegal-immigrant-shortage California's Illegal Immigrant Shortage], BusinessWeek, May 3, 2012</ref> [[Illegal immigration to the United States|Illegal]] [[Alien (law)|alien]] constituted an estimated 7.3 percent of the state's population, the third highest percentage of any state in the [[Illegal immigrant population of the United States|country]],<ref>{{Cite news | first=Peter | last=Slevin | title=New Arizona law puts police in 'tenuous' spot | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/graphic/2010/04/29/GR2010042904397.html?sid=ST2010042905051|work=Washington Post | location=Washington, DC | pages= A4 | date=April 30, 2010 }}</ref><ref group="note">behind Nevada and Arizona</ref> totaling nearly 2.6 million.<ref name="SDUT19042011">{{cite news |title=Cutting services to illegal immigrants isn't easy |author=Michael Gardner |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2011/apr/19/cutting-services-to-illegal-immigrants-isn't-easy/ |newspaper=[[San Diego Union Tribune]] |date=April 19, 2011 |accessdate=April 22, 2011}}</ref> More than half originate from Mexico.<ref name="SDUT19042011" /> Illegal aliens make up more than ten percent of the population in [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles]], [[Monterey County, California|Monterey]], [[San Benito County, California|San Benito]], [[Imperial County, California|Imperial]], and [[Napa County, California|Napa]] Counties – the latter four of which have significant agricultural industries that depend on manual labor.<ref name="PPIC2011II">{{cite web |url=http://www.ppic.org/content/pubs/atissue/AI_711HJAI.pdf |title=Illegal Immigration |last1=Johnson |first1=Hans |last2=Hill |first2=Laura |date=July 2011 |work=Publications |publisher=[[Public Policy Institute of California]] |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref>

===Racial and ancestral makeup===
According to the U.S. Census Bureau in 2011:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/06000.html |title=California QuickFacts from the US Census Bureau |publisher=Quickfacts.census.gov |year=2011 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref>
* 74.0% [[White American|White]] <small>(39.7% [[Non-Hispanic Whites|Non-Hispanic White]], 34.3% [[White Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic White]])</small>
* 13.6% [[Asian American|Asian]] <small>(3% [[Filipino American|Filipino]], 3% [[Chinese American|Chinese]],  1.6% [[Vietnamese American|Vietnamese]], 1.4% [[Indian American|Indian]], 1.2% [[Korean American|Korean]], 0.7% [[Japanese American|Japanese]], 0.2% [[Hmong American|Hmong]], 0.2% [[Cambodian American|Cambodian]], 0.2% [[Laotian American|Laotian]], 0.1% [[Thai American|Thai]], 0.1% [[Pakistani American|Pakistani]])</small>
* 6.6% Black or [[African American]]
* 1.7% [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]
* 3.6% [[Multiracial American|Multiracial]] <small>(1.3% White and "Some Other Race", 1.2% White and Asian, 0.6% White and Native American, 0.5% White and Black, 1.3% Other)</small>
* 0.5% [[Native Hawaiian]] or [[Pacific Islander American|Pacific Islander]] <small>(0.1% [[Samoan American|Samoan]], 0.1% [[Guamanian]] or [[Chamorro people|Chamorro]], 0.1% Native Hawaiian, 0.2% "Other Pacific Islander")</small>
* 38.1% are [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] (of any race) <small>(31% [[Mexican American|Mexican]], 1.5% Salvadoran, 0.9% Guatemalan, 0.5% Puerto Rican, 0.3% Nicaraguan, 0.2% Honduran, 0.2% Cuban, 0.2% Colombian, 0.2% Peruvian)</small>
* 61.9% of the population is Non-Hispanic (of any race)

The principal ancestries of California's residents in 2009 has been surveyed to be:<ref>{{cite web|publisher=American FactFinder, United States Census Bureau |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/ADPTable?_bm=y&-context=adp&-qr_name=ACS_2009_3YR_G00_DP3YR2&-ds_name=ACS_2009_3YR_G00_&-tree_id=3309&-redoLog=true&-_caller=geoselect&-geo_id=04000US06&-format=&-_lang=en |title=California – Selected Social Characteristics in the United States: 2007–2009 |accessdate=November 2, 2011}}</ref>
* 31% [[Mexican American|Mexican]]
* 10% [[German American|German]]
* 8% [[Irish American|Irish]]
* 7% [[English American|English]]
* 4% [[Italian American|Italian]]

With regard to demographics, California has the largest population of White Americans in the U.S., an estimated 22,200,000 residents, although most demographic surveys do not measure actual genetic ancestry. The state has the 5th largest population of African Americans in the U.S., an estimated 2,250,000 residents. California's Asian American population is estimated at 4.4 million, about a third of the nation's 13 million Asian Americans. California's Native American population of 285,000 is the most of any state.<ref name="US Census Cal Race and Ethnicity">{{cite web
  | title = California – ACS Demographic and Housing Estimates: 2006–2008
  | work = American Fact Finder
  | publisher = US Census Bureau
  | url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/ADPTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=04000US06&-qr_name=ACS_2008_3YR_G00_DP3YR5&-ds_name=ACS_2008_3YR_G00_&-_lang=en&-_sse=on
  | accessdate =December 26, 2009}}</ref> While the population of minorities accounts for 102 million of 301 million U.S. residents, 20% of the national total live in California.<ref name="US Census Cal Race and Ethnicity"/><ref name="US Census US Race and Ethnicity">{{cite web
  | title = United States – ACS Demographic and Housing Estimates: 2006–2008
  | work = American Fact Finder
  | publisher = US Census Bureau
  | url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/ADPTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=01000US&-qr_name=ACS_2008_3YR_G00_DP3YR5&-ds_name=ACS_2008_3YR_G00_&-_lang=en&-redoLog=false&-_sse=on
  | accessdate =December 26, 2009}}</ref>

According to estimates from 2011, California has the largest [[Majority-minority state|minority population]] in the United States by numbers, making up 60% of the state population.<ref name="CensusQuickFacts">{{cite web
  | title = California QuickFacts from the US Census Bureau:
  | publisher = US Census Bureau
  | url = http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/06000.html
  | accessdate =December 26, 2009}}</ref> In 2000, [[Hispanic and Latino American|Hispanics]] comprised 32% of the population; that number grew to 38% in 2011.<ref>"[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/06/05/MNSG1DQ1BL.DTL Whites in state 'below the replacement' level]". [[San Francisco Chronicle]]. June 5, 2010.</ref> [[Non-Hispanic whites]] decreased from 80% of the state's population in 1970 to 40% in 2011.<ref name="CensusQuickFacts"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2001/03/30/national/main282687.shtml |title=Whites Now A Minority In California|publisher=Cbsnews.com |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=September 2, 2012}}</ref>

The population younger than age 1 was 75% minority in 2011.<ref>"[http://www.cleveland.com/datacentral/index.ssf/2012/06/americas_under_age_1_populatio.html Americans under age 1 now mostly minorities, but not in Ohio: Statistical Snapshot]". ''[[The Plain Dealer]]''. June 3, 2012.</ref> Approximately 26% of California's [[State school|public school]] students in the 2011–12 school year identified themselves as white (non-Hispanic), and 52% of the state's students identified themselves as Hispanic or Latino. The following ethnic groups that made up the statewide public school student body were Asians (11%), African Americans (7%), Native Americans (0.7%), and Pacific Islanders (0.6%). Students of mixed race made up 2% of the public schools. Hispanics made up the majority of the state's public schools since 2010. [[Los Angeles Unified School District]], the largest school district in California and second largest in the nation, is 73% Hispanic, 10% African American, 9% non-Hispanic Caucasian, 6% Asian, 0.5% Native American, and 0.4% Pacific Islander.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=California Department of Education|url=http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/Enrollment/EthnicEnr.aspx?cYear=2011-12&cGender=B&cType=ALL&cChoice=StEnrEth2|title=Enrollment by Ethnicity for 2011–12: Statewide Enrollment by Ethnicity (with county data) |accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref>

===Languages===
{| class="wikitable sortable" style="margin-left:1em; float:right"
|+ '''Top 10 Non-English Languages Spoken in California'''
|-
